---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const siteName = import.meta.env.PUBLIC_SITE_NAME ?? "PricingNest";
const lastReviewed = "2026-03-30";
const siteUrl = (Astro.site?.toString() ?? import.meta.env.PUBLIC_SITE_URL ?? "https://pricingnest.com").replace(/\/$/, "");
const canonical = new URL(Astro.url.pathname, siteUrl).toString();
const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  name: `About ${siteName}`,
  url: canonical,
  description: "Editorial methodology, review standards, and correction policy for PricingNest calculators and guides.",
  dateModified: lastReviewed,
  mainEntity: {
    "@type": "Organization",
    name: siteName,
    url: siteUrl
  }
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`About | ${siteName}`}
  description="How PricingNest builds, reviews, and maintains SaaS pricing calculators, unit-economics models, and supporting guides."
>
  <script slot="head" type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(jsonLd)} />
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>About {siteName}</h1>
    <p>
      {siteName} is an editorial toolkit for SaaS pricing, packaging, and unit economics. The site is built to help
      founders, product teams, finance partners, and operators work through pricing decisions with transparent formulas,
      plain-English guidance, and reviewable assumptions.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      For the full methodology and review policy, see <a href="/methodology/">Methodology</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">Last reviewed: {lastReviewed}</p>
  </section>

  <div class="grid">
    <section class="card col8">
      <h2>Quick navigation</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li><a href="#editorial-team">Editorial responsibility</a></li>
        <li><a href="#how-calculators-are-built">How calculators are built</a></li>
        <li><a href="#review-policy">How pages are reviewed</a></li>
        <li><a href="#corrections-policy">Corrections and updates</a></li>
        <li><a href="/methodology/">Methodology and review policy</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Who this site is for</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        PricingNest is designed for teams that need faster first-pass pricing analysis without hiding the math. The goal
        is not to replace finance modeling or customer research. It is to make common pricing decisions easier to test,
        explain, and review with other stakeholders.
      </p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Why this site exists</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        PricingNest exists to make pricing models easier to inspect, challenge, and explain. Many pricing calculators on
        the web give a number without showing the assumptions behind it. This site is maintained so operators can see the
        inputs, understand the tradeoffs, and review a first-pass decision before it turns into packaging, pricing-page,
        or finance work.
      </p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Who should use PricingNest</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        The site is intended for founders, pricing operators, product teams, finance partners, and GTM leads who need a
        transparent starting point for SaaS pricing and unit-economics decisions. It is most useful when a team already
        has internal cost or usage assumptions and needs a clearer way to review them together.
      </p>

      <h2 id="editorial-team" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Editorial responsibility</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        PricingNest content is maintained by the <strong>PricingNest Editorial Team</strong>. The team is responsible for
        calculator inputs, explanatory copy, retained guides, glossary definitions, and update decisions across the site.
        The goal is to make each page clear enough for a founder, operator, or finance partner to review the assumptions
        without relying on black-box output.
      </p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Who maintains the site</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        PricingNest is maintained as an editorial product rather than an open directory. The <strong>PricingNest Editorial
        Team</strong> is responsible for retained tool pages, methodology updates, linked glossary terms, and correction
        handling. When a page is marked reviewed, the editorial team is saying that the formulas, assumptions, and next-step
        guidance were checked together as one decision-support surface.
      </p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">How the site is operated</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        PricingNest is operated as a maintained reference and calculator property, not as a user-generated directory. We
        publish and revise pages when they help clarify a real pricing decision, not just to expand page count. The
        operating goal is to keep the strongest tools, supporting guides, and core glossary definitions aligned enough to
        be useful together.
      </p>

      <h2 id="how-calculators-are-built" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">How calculators are built</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Every calculator is built from explicit inputs, formulas, and assumptions instead of hidden vendor feeds.</li>
        <li>Default examples are meant to demonstrate logic, not to substitute for your own contracts, usage, or cloud bills.</li>
        <li>Core pages link to guides and glossary terms so the decision context stays next to the math.</li>
        <li>When a model is simplified, the page should say what is excluded and when deeper validation is still required.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="review-policy" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">How pages are reviewed</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Core pages are reviewed for clarity, output usefulness, and consistency with related guides and glossary terms.</li>
        <li>We surface who reviewed a page and when it was last reviewed on retained guides and glossary entries.</li>
        <li>Tool pages are reviewed for formula clarity, input usefulness, and whether the next-step links still support the main decision.</li>
        <li>We treat a meaningful update as a change to formulas, assumptions, examples, guidance, or trust-critical wording, not a cosmetic edit.</li>
        <li>What counts as a reviewed update includes a formula change, a modeling assumption change, a revised default example, a rewritten interpretation block, or a trust-critical wording fix.</li>
        <li>What changed when a review date is refreshed should be material to the reader's decision, not just a formatting cleanup.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Editorial standards</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>We favor transparent assumptions over black-box estimates or SEO-first filler copy.</li>
        <li>We connect calculators, guides, and glossary terms so the same concept is explained consistently across the site.</li>
        <li>We revise pages when examples are unclear, assumptions are missing, or the content no longer helps pricing teams.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="corrections-policy" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Corrections and updates</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        If a formula, example, explanation, or linked resource is wrong or unclear, use the contact page to send a
        correction request. We review correction notes before updating retained pages, and we update visible review dates
        when the change affects the substance of the page.
      </p>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Use <a href="/contact/">the contact page</a> for calculator feedback, corrections, or unclear wording.</li>
        <li>We prioritize corrections that affect formulas, interpretation, assumptions, or navigation to related resources.</li>
        <li>When a meaningful update changes decision guidance, we refresh the review date rather than silently editing the page.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">How we handle feedback</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Feedback is reviewed as editorial input, not as a consulting engagement. We may use correction notes to improve a
        single page, adjust a related guide, tighten wording across similar pages, or de-emphasize content that no longer
        adds enough value. Not every message leads to a visible update, but trust-critical reports are prioritized.
      </p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Limitations</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Tools provide estimates only and should be validated against your own financials, contracts, and usage data.</li>
        <li>We do not model every cost category by default, including payment fees, support escalation, taxes, or vendor minimums.</li>
        <li>Results can change materially by customer segment, geography, workload pattern, and discount policy.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">What this site does not replace</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        PricingNest does not replace finance review, customer research, contract review, legal review, or direct vendor
        billing validation. The site is meant to make a pricing conversation sharper before a team commits to a live
        pricing change, not to act as the final source of truth for revenue decisions.
      </p>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Report a correction</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        If you spot a modeling issue, unclear explanation, or page that needs updating, use the contact page to send a
        correction request. Feedback helps us improve formulas, assumptions, and wording before the same problem spreads
        across multiple pages.
      </p>
      <p class="muted">
        Editorial contact: <strong>PricingNest Editorial Team</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="muted">
        For operational questions, correction requests, or page-quality concerns, use the <a href="/contact/">Contact</a>
        page so we can route the issue through the same review path used for retained content.
      </p>
    </section>

    <aside class="card col4">
      <h2>Quick links</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li><a href="/saas-pricing/">All tools</a></li>
        <li><a href="/guides/">Guide library</a></li>
        <li><a href="/glossary/">Glossary</a></li>
        <li><a href="/privacy-policy/">Privacy policy</a></li>
        <li><a href="/cookie-policy/">Cookie policy</a></li>
        <li><a href="/terms/">Terms</a></li>
        <li><a href="/contact/">Contact</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">Trust checklist</h2>
      <ul class="list">
        <li>Check the visible review or update date on retained pages.</li>
        <li>Compare assumptions against your own usage and contracts before sharing a model.</li>
        <li>Follow linked guides and glossary terms when a metric or pricing unit needs more context.</li>
        <li>Use the correction route if a retained page is unclear or outdated.</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
